{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "bcf5bbc2-453a-417f-8d63-33d209a1f58c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Think of it like this:\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine a movie theatre 🎬\n",
    "\n",
    "You are the manager of a movie theatre.\n",
    "\n",
    "Every 5 minutes, you write down how many people are sitting in each row.\n",
    "\n",
    "Time\tRow A\tRow B\tRow C\tRow D\n",
    "9:15\t20\t25\t28\t30\n",
    "9:20\t21\t?\t29\t31\n",
    "9:25\t22\t26\t?\t32\n",
    "\n",
    "One day, some numbers disappear.\n",
    "\n",
    "Could you guess them?\n",
    "\n",
    "Probably yes.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why?\n",
    "\n",
    "Because:\n",
    "\n",
    "* Row B at 9:20 should be close to Row B at 9:15 and 9:25.\n",
    "* Row B should also be similar to nearby rows A and C.\n",
    "* People don’t magically appear or disappear by hundreds in 5 minutes.\n",
    "\n",
    "So even if data is missing, there are patterns around it.\n",
    "\n",
    "Your project is doing exactly this, except instead of movie audience counts, you have Implied Volatility (IV) values.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 1: What is an option?\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine Nifty is currently at 26,000.\n",
    "\n",
    "Your friend says:\n",
    "\n",
    "“I think Nifty will go up next week.”\n",
    "\n",
    "So he buys a Call Option (CE).\n",
    "\n",
    "Another friend says:\n",
    "\n",
    "“I think Nifty will go down.”\n",
    "\n",
    "So she buys a Put Option (PE).\n",
    "\n",
    "These are basically bets on market movement.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 2: What is strike price?\n",
    "\n",
    "Think of strike price as the target number.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "* 25200 CE\n",
    "* 25500 CE\n",
    "* 25800 CE\n",
    "* 26100 CE\n",
    "\n",
    "If Nifty is currently 26,000:\n",
    "\n",
    "* 25800 is close to current market\n",
    "* 26100 is slightly above\n",
    "* 25200 is far below\n",
    "\n",
    "Just like seats in a theatre have row numbers, options have strike prices.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 3: What is Implied Volatility (IV)?\n",
    "\n",
    "This is where most beginners get confused.\n",
    "\n",
    "Forget finance for a moment.\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine two roads:\n",
    "\n",
    "Road A\n",
    "\n",
    "Very calm.\n",
    "\n",
    "Almost no traffic.\n",
    "\n",
    "Road B\n",
    "\n",
    "Crazy traffic.\n",
    "\n",
    "Lots of accidents.\n",
    "\n",
    "Very unpredictable.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you were selling insurance for cars, which road would have more expensive insurance?\n",
    "\n",
    "Road B.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because more uncertainty = more risk.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "The stock market works the same way.\n",
    "\n",
    "IV simply measures:\n",
    "\n",
    "“How much movement does the market expect in the future?”\n",
    "\n",
    "Higher uncertainty → Higher IV.\n",
    "\n",
    "Lower uncertainty → Lower IV.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "* IV = 0.10 → market expects small moves\n",
    "* IV = 0.20 → market expects bigger moves\n",
    "* IV = 0.30 → market expects huge moves\n",
    "\n",
    "So IV is basically a fear/uncertainty meter.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 4: What does one row of your dataset mean?\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose one timestamp looks like:\n",
    "\n",
    "Strike\tIV\n",
    "25200 CE\t0.21\n",
    "25400 CE\t0.18\n",
    "25600 CE\t0.15\n",
    "25800 CE\t0.13\n",
    "26000 CE\t0.12\n",
    "26200 CE\t0.13\n",
    "26400 CE\t0.16\n",
    "26600 CE\t0.20\n",
    "\n",
    "If you draw this, it looks like a smile 😊\n",
    "\n",
    "Low in the middle.\n",
    "\n",
    "High on both sides.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is called the volatility smile.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why?\n",
    "\n",
    "Because options near the current market price are traded a lot and are easier to price.\n",
    "\n",
    "Options far away from the market are riskier, so they get higher IV.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 5: Why is predicting missing values possible?\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose your data becomes:\n",
    "\n",
    "Strike\tIV\n",
    "25200 CE\t0.21\n",
    "25400 CE\t0.18\n",
    "25600 CE\t?\n",
    "25800 CE\t0.13\n",
    "26000 CE\t0.12\n",
    "\n",
    "What could the missing value be?\n",
    "\n",
    "Probably around:\n",
    "\n",
    "0.14–0.16\n",
    "\n",
    "because it sits between:\n",
    "\n",
    "* 0.18\n",
    "* 0.13\n",
    "\n",
    "You wouldn’t suddenly expect:\n",
    "\n",
    "* 0.50\n",
    "* 1.20\n",
    "* 0.01\n",
    "\n",
    "That would break the smooth smile shape.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 6: Time also helps\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine:\n",
    "\n",
    "Time\t26000 CE IV\n",
    "9:15\t0.12\n",
    "9:20\t?\n",
    "9:25\t0.13\n",
    "\n",
    "Could 9:20 be 0.90?\n",
    "\n",
    "Probably not.\n",
    "\n",
    "Markets don’t usually jump that much in 5 minutes.\n",
    "\n",
    "So the missing value is likely around:\n",
    "\n",
    "0.12–0.13\n",
    "\n",
    "This is called temporal continuity.\n",
    "\n",
    "Values change smoothly over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 7: Your dataset has two kinds of clues\n",
    "\n",
    "When a value is missing, you can look:\n",
    "\n",
    "Left and right (other strikes)\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "25200 → 0.20\n",
    "\n",
    "25400 → 0.18\n",
    "\n",
    "25600 → ?\n",
    "\n",
    "25800 → 0.14\n",
    "\n",
    "This gives strike-based information.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "Up and down (other timestamps)\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "9:15 → 0.16\n",
    "\n",
    "9:20 → ?\n",
    "\n",
    "9:25 → 0.17\n",
    "\n",
    "This gives time-based information.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "A good model uses both.\n",
    "\n",
    "⸻\n",
    "\n",
    "The whole project in one sentence\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine a giant Excel sheet where:\n",
    "\n",
    "* Rows = time\n",
    "* Columns = option strikes\n",
    "* Cells = IV values\n",
    "\n",
    "Some cells are blank.\n",
    "\n",
    "Your job is to learn the smooth patterns across time and strikes and then intelligently fill in the missing IV values, just like guessing missing audience counts in a theatre by looking at nearby rows and nearby times.\n",
    "\n",
    "That’s the core idea behind the entire assignment."
   ]
  },
  {
